y, much broader—and more gender inclusive—than we normally think today. In doing so, The Philosopher challenges us to reconsider our idea of what philosophers can do and what counts as philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPhilosophers. 0aPhilosophyxHistory. 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh  aADINA.  aAge of Enlightenment.  aAllusion.  aAmerican philosophy.  aAnalytic philosophy.  aAnimism.  aAphorism.  aAristotle.  aAsceticism.  aAtheism.  aAxial Age.  aBertrand Russell.  aBuddhism and Christianity.  aBuddhism.  aCareer.  aConsciousness.  aCritique.  aD. Graham Burnett.  aDemocritus.  aDetermination.  aDialectical materialism.  aEpicurus.  aEpistemology.  aEthics.  aEtymology.  aExistence.  aExistentialism.  aExperimental philosophy.  aExpert.  aExplanation.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aGood and evil.  aHenry More.  aHuman science.  aHumanities.  aImmanuel Kant.  aInclination (ethics).  aIndian philosophy.  aIndividualism.  aInference.  aIpso facto.  aJacques Derrida.  aJohn Rawls.  aLiterature.  aMaterialism.  aMetaphor.  aMethodology.  aModern philosophy.  aMutatis mutandis.  aNarrative.  aNatural magic.  aNatural philosophy.  aNatural science.  aOf Education.  aOntology.  aPaul Guyer.  aPhenomenon.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophical progress.  aPhilosophy Today.  aPhilosophy of life.  aPhilosophy of science.  aPhilosophy.  aPolitical philosophy.  aPositivism.  aPotentiality and actuality.  aPractical philosophy.  aPragmatism.  aPre-Socratic philosophy.  aPrinciple.  aProse.  aRationality.  aReason.  aReligion.  aResult.  aSanskrit.  aScholasticism.  aSchool of thought.  aScience.  aSophism.  aSophist.  aStephen